   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "The short answer is: **Stars twinkle because of Earth's atmosphere.**\n",
      "\n",
      "The scientific name for this phenomenon is **atmospheric scintillation**. Here is the step-by-step breakdown of why it happens:\n",
      "\n",
      "### 1. Stars are \"Point Sources\"\n",
      "Stars are incredibly massive, but they are so far away that they appear to our eyes as tiny, single points of light. Because the light coming from them is a very thin, concentrated beam, it is easily disturbed.\n",
      "\n",
      "### 2. The Atmosphere is \"Turbulent\"\n",
      "Earth's atmosphere is not one solid block of air. It is made of many layers of gas and wind. These layers vary in:\n",
      "*   **Temperature:** Warm air and cold air have different densities.\n",
      "*   **Density:** Thicker air bends light differently than thinner air.\n",
      "*   **Movement:** Wind is constantly shifting these pockets of air around.\n",
      "\n",
      "### 3. The \"Bending\" of Light (Refraction)\n",
      "As a star's beam of light enters our atmosphere, it has to pass through these shifting layers of air. Every time the light hits a pocket of air with a different temperature or density, it **bends (refracts)** slightly.\n",
      "\n",
      "Because the air is constantly moving, the light beam is bent in different directions many times per second. To your eye, this makes the star seem to:\n",
      "*   Shift position slightly.\n",
      "*   Change in brightness.\n",
      "*   Change in color (slightly).\n",
      "\n",
      "Your brain perceives these rapid changes as **twinkling**.\n",
      "\n",
      "---\n",
      "\n",
      "### Fun Fact: Why don't planets twinkle?\n",
      "If you look at a bright \"star\" in the sky and notice it is shining with a steady, flat light, it is likely a **planet** (like Jupiter or Venus).\n",
      "\n",
      "Planets don't twinkle because they are much closer to Earth. Instead of being a single \"point\" of light, they appear as tiny **disks**. \n",
      "\n",
      "While the light from one edge of the planet's disk might be bending one way, the light from the other edge is bending another way. These opposite movements **cancel each other out**, resulting in a steady glow.\n",
      "\n",
      "**Summary:** \n",
      "*   **Stars** = Point source $\\rightarrow$ Light bends easily $\\rightarrow$ **Twinkle**\n",
      "*   **Planets** = Disk source $\\rightarrow$ Light bends cancel out $\\rightarrow$ **Steady**\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
